For the final list of risk zoonoses, 3 of the original 30 agents (Hendra virus, Menangle virus, and 
 Rickettsia prowazekii) were removed because few, if any, genera were found to harbor these infections; the final tables therefore include 27 diseases (
 Tables 1â€“
 3). The risk zoonoses capable of infecting the greatest number of genera were: rabies viruses, in 78 genera; 
 Bacillus anthracis, the causative agent of anthrax, in 57 genera; 
 Mycobacterium tuberculosis complex, in 48 genera; 
 Echinococcus spp., the agents of hydatid cyst disease, in 41 genera; 
 Leptospira spp., in 35 genera; 
 Brucella spp., the agents of undulant fever, in 32 genera; 
 Francisella tularensis, the agent of tularemia, in 31 genera; Crimean-Congo hemorrhagic fever virus, in 27 genera; 
 Y. pestis, the agent of plague, in 24 genera; and 
 Coxiella burnetii, the agent of Q fever, in 20 genera (
 Table 2; 
 Technical Appendix).
